reviews.text: This place is simple and awesome. As in filled with awe.

Won't address what I think about the institution but will talk only about the building, which is absolutely AMAZING. One of the most beautiful architectures in the city and in Israel, with a lot of natural light and a lot of symbols and meaning in how it was built. A gift for any photographer of architecture lover, views on the city and beautiful garden nearby as a bonus (also, worth checking the building from the outside and don't miss the courtyard!).
Free daily tours that are open to the general public take place at 11 a.m. in Hebrew and at 12 noon in English.
Accessibility: accessible parking, entrance to the building, toilets, water stations, voice guidance system, audio assistance system at the reception, directing signage, audio systems in courtrooms.
I believe everyone in Israel's supreme court should watch Lauren Southern's video on why feminism is an antynom for equality. Feminism is a movement for entitlements and supremacy.
They got a illuminati thing on top that aint cool. Flip the (bad) jews in here
Very impressive. Highly recommend the guided tour is about 1 hour long. Free.

Very peaceful place, you can come on good weather day and sit at the bank of river along the pathways. Moreover this place is dedicated to Rizal, there is a museum inside about his life and his last days in the same prison. The structures in this fort are impressive and unique. The idea of having wall around the fort was to protect it from enemies to enter.
I'm so glad that my grade 4 sister appreciate the place so much. It's a nice place for children. They will learn while having fun at the same time 😊

There is an entrance fee of 50 pesos. Best time to go there would be by 5pm onwards because of the lights and it makes the place a little romantic and if you want to relax or just want to have some time off to think then you can visit the place. There is a bicycle rental and the place is also historical. Good place to take pictures.
Very well maintained. Very cool piece of history. I highly recommend visiting if you are in the area. Worth all of the 75 pesos to get in.

An excellent and beautiful place to visit if you want to learn more about the history of the Philippines. Make sure to get a guide so that you can have a better understanding of everything that you are looking at. Enjoy!
I was invited to a special wedding that was held after hours. So the place can be rented. It was beautiful. Yet, one can sence the rustic history of the surroundings.

There is a mininal fee collected at the entrance. You can go around to take pictures or read about the place's history on commemorative plaques. 

Bonus tip: Look for the security guard assigned named Bong. He is quite good on a camera.
Very beautiful and well-maintained. And very serene, peaceful surroundings too
Ruins with a lot of history being raised and restored multiple times. Beautiful views over the golf course and the city.
Good for photo opps. Its a Historical place of Manila.
I have fond memory here training for the computerization of the voters registration during the 2004 elections. Great times.

Old Spanish colonial government building destroyed during WW2. This was the official residence of the Spanish Governor-General assigned to the Philippines during the Spanish colonial era. The only surviving part of this building is its facade.
It’s near to a cathedral.
One of the historical places during spanish time.
Historic place and nice view.. Just take a picture with your camera or just take a picture with your selfie stick...

This is the world heritage site. There are a lot of catholic fine arts in the museum. Start at the entrance and walk through the galleries, do not miss to go up the choir balcony, you will find out the great view of the church. Worth the ticket,  200 piso.

The church looks old and wonderful with western ancient design. It might look simple from outside but you must explore the nice architecture inside. You would observe 3D painting on the ceiling. During my visit, there was a wedding ceremony which make me know how famous this church is.

Oldest Church in the Philippines, try to visit their museum full of Catholic antiques created by various known and unknown artists. It’s a little dingy and spooky inside because everything is century dated or so. You would also see different architecture design of the churches over the past century. Overall it’s a historical place and a must see for the students.

If you are a historian, better visit this place. You wont need a guide since the description are detailed here. Entrance fee is 200peso per person which is worth to get to know the 450 years old history. There are nearby attraction too.

Worth the travel!! It’s absolutely beatiful. The church is filled with beatiful paintings covering all the walls and ceiling. Pay only P200 to enter the museum and if you like arts and history, this is an absolute gem. They have paintings, statues, musical instruments, china, books from 1700-1900 and you get to really see them up close and even touch some of them! Best museum experience ever. The structure of the building is just breathtaking, feels like you’re in Harry Potter... or maybe The Nun. Drop by and you won’t regret it!
A good place to learn the history of Philippines. Make sure that you hire a guide also so that you will understand the significance of each of the exhibit and the enjoy the history better.
Beautiful colonial house. Nice explanation from one of the guys around the kitchen.

If you're ever to visit Metro Manila Philippine, this is a must place to go. It's so packed with history but not only that, it's also a cozy spot  to move  around and appreciate the beautiful architecture that wrapped the surrounding building. This is such a wonderful place and you'll  definitely enjoy your visit.

We were not so lucky because of the rains, so can not walking around inside the Casa Manila so well but for sure in love with the building architecture. They have museum, coffee shop, restaurant and souvenirs shop inside, free entry to come in here but to enter the museum you have to pay for the ticket. Its very Instable, don't miss your opportunity to take the pics infront of the building, you will in loveee..
Nice museum. A little window into colonial life in Manila.
I learned facts here that I’ve never learned from my history/Rizal class back in school. Or maybe I haven’t read that much. Well, it’s never too late to learn.

Sometimes this serves as a haven for Photographers who would visit the Intramuros Area especially during dusk
The ruins of the aduana building reminds me of the spanish era. Their just ruins but it was so beautiful. Just another spanish colonial structure in the walled city.
great place😉

I love the ruins!! Although a bit disappointed that the inside of the run down building is not properly maintained. It could have more value if the insides are cleared of the wild grasses, plants growing inside and clutter. Hope the City and National government do something about it.
It's so beautiful here...

They could not handle  a lot of people.  Service time is from 45 minutes to  over an hour. 

The taste is not that good. The quality of the Pizza was not that good either.

Everything I tried was delicious!

Chicken Meal had crunchy, slightly salty skin with reasonably soft white meat.

Lasagna is the best part of my experience because of the serving size, how hot it was when it was served, and the cheesiness. Ending it with a bread stick makes me feel less thirsty.

A delicious Berry Slush helps me fight the hot weather. It's sweet and very cold!
Nice ambient and the place are inside the tourist attractions of intramuros..  The food are great and tasty and affordable..
Delicious pizza here...
Best

Went there to avail our gift certificates. Average food but a bit pricey..staffs are not so accommodating. Takes time to serve orders and bill though not much customers. The place is peaceful though, good for private meetings or just personal time.
tried it out because of booky, but service is really bad, small serving sizes, and overpriced food
We waited for too long, and was served with not so hot dish... Food is not good and expensive. Wifi is strong.

We wait for a while, but food is not so hot, WHY?
We ordered pasta, and I wouldn’t recommend if you want to try.
The price is not included TAX, and the extra fee is 22% of your cost!
The food is salty and cold, and the tax is not included. We are super disappointed by the meal. The only one star is for the free wifi.

A Restaurant located at the Intramuros area. Authentic Filipino as well Western  meals are served in this place. Good food, adequate portions. If the service is on time the missing 🌟 will be added. Great selection of traditional Filipino desert. The food description is interconnected with the Filipino language as well with the Church related linguistics names.

Good location in Intramuros, and the place definitely has character. The menu is somewhat confusing, it seems each dish is names after a member of the clergy and there are no explanation of the Filipino dishes (reasonable to expect this in a place that must get tourists), that said the selection was varied with plenty of western dishes. The food was good, the price was reasonable and the eccentricities welcome given how homogenised dinning is in Manila.

A great way to start the day. Or night. Your choice. The ingredients run and swirl together, amplifying each other's flavor. Got a pretty good portion size for a relatively affordable price. Should definitely try this place out if you have time to kill.

Very disappointed with the service & staff. The desserts were too sweet. Servings of dishes were quite small. Very slow service. But the most unacceptable & disgusting part was the very rude security guard assigned on 8th March 2019. We ate there & went out, but then decided that we need to go to the loo/toilet, then after that we went out again to finally leave the place. On my way out, the very rude security guard started screaming saying that we were wasting & using their water supply & we are not customers and he went on & on screaming the same lines. Good thing I took photos & showed the guard that we just ate there and we even bought some takeaway desserts. But then the damage has been done and he didn't even apologise. I was shocked that the staff or owner didn't do anything to stop the guard from this horrible behaviour. I suggest that the owner of this restaurant should send this guard for "code of conduct training." Based on the code "He shall not use his license & other privileges if any, to the prejudice of the public, the client or the customer & his agency." As a paying customer I will definitely "not recommend" this horrible restaurant. Worst experience ever!
Pinakbet pizza is worth checking out.
One of my must-shop spots in Bardstown every time I go!! I always find something to buy at Barbara's!!
Beautiful decor and friendly service

Love walking into a Starbucks and smelling the fresh coffee. This location was clean and the staff friendly. Coffee was made to order and correctly made for this picky coffee drinker lol. This spot has an area for when you are wanting to socialize or break out the computer/books and do some studying while sipping on a latte. Only problem I seen was the drive through and parking area are very tight but couldn't take a star away just for that. Keep it up at this location cause my little girl and I will definitely be back for our coffee.
Always fast, friendly, and informative! Their coffee is great and their snacks are always yummy! Mobile pickup through their app is always very convenient as well!

Rude, impersonal staff, slow service, dirty restrooms. The food is blah, you get better quality food at much lower prices at McDonalds or any of the other fast food chains in the area.
Situated in the heart of city.Awesome place to hangout with friends. Friends can sit together for long time . Burgers are awesome in taste. All food items are good in taste.
Love to come here, after my coaching classes. It is very nice place for sitting with friends
